  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">All four entities (`sprk_action`, `sprk_actiontemplate`, `sprk_actioninstance`, `sprk_actionrun`) exist in the dev environment; verified by Web API GET on each EntityDefinition.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`sprk_actionrun.status` Choice has exactly the 6 ADR-017 values: `Queued | Running | Completed | Failed | Poisoned | Cancelled` — no extras, no omissions.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`sprk_action.playbookId` lookup resolves against existing `sprk_aiplaybook` entity; cascade behavior is Referential Restrict (deletion of referenced Playbook is blocked); verified by attempting and observing the block.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">All four entities carry the `tenantId` text field marked required (NFR-05).</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Solution exported to `src/dataverse/solutions/...` round-trips cleanly: pack → unpack → diff shows no drift.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`docs/data-model/action-engine-entities.md` exists with entity-by-entity field list + ERD diagram of the four entities + the `sprk_aiplaybook` FK.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Baseline build still passes: `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/` exits 0.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The Action sits **above** the Playbook (Action.playbookId → sprk_aiplaybook). This is the inverse of any "Playbook owns Action" wording you might see in older drafts — confirm against design §5 + coordination-assessment-with-insights-engine.md §4.1.

    Use Referential Restrict (NOT Cascade Delete) on `sprk_action.playbookId` — deletion of a Playbook with referencing Actions MUST be blocked. This protects Action Definitions from accidental Playbook cleanup.

    JSON fields (parameterValues, triggerSpec payload, etc.) are stored as Text(Memo) with `Format = TextArea`. The BFF deserializes via System.Text.Json. There is no Dataverse-native JSON type.

    Do NOT add Dataverse plugins to any of these entities. ADR-002 keeps plugins thin (no HTTP/Graph calls); Action triggers will be handled by webhooks in R2.

    The `dataverse-create-schema` skill handles the EntityDefinitions Web API + Python SDK patterns. Don't try to use PAC CLI for table creation — `pac table create` and `pac column create` don't exist.

    `coordination-assessment-with-insights-engine.md` §4.1 confirms Action.playbookId FK direction. Do not change it without revisiting that document.
  </notes>

